[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] In geometry, a **hyperplane** is a generalization of a two-dimensional plane in three-dimensional space to mathematical spaces of arbitrary dimension.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] Like a plane in space, a hyperplane is a flat hypersurface, a subspace whose dimension is one less than that of the ambient space.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] Two lower-dimensional examples of hyperplanes are one-dimensional lines in a plane and zero-dimensional points on a line.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] Most commonly, the ambient space is n-dimensional Euclidean space, in which case the hyperplanes are the (*n* − 1)-dimensional "flats", each of which separates the space into two half spaces.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] A reflection across a hyperplane is a kind of motion (geometric transformation preserving distance between points), and the group of all motions is generated by the reflections.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] A convex polytope is the intersection of half-spaces.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] In non-Euclidean geometry, the ambient space might be the n-dimensional sphere or hyperbolic space, or more generally a pseudo-Riemannian space form, and the hyperplanes are the hypersurfaces consisting of all geodesics through a point which are perpendicular to a specific normal geodesic.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] In other kinds of ambient spaces, some properties from Euclidean space are no longer relevant.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] For example, in affine space, there is no concept of distance, so there are no reflections or motions.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] In a non-orientable space such as elliptic space or projective space, there is no concept of half-planes.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] In greatest generality, the notion of hyperplane is meaningful in any mathematical space in which the concept of the dimension of a subspace is defined.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] The difference in dimension between a subspace and its ambient space is known as its *codimension*.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] In geometry, a **hyperplane** of an *n*-dimensional space *V* is a subspace of dimension *n* − 1, or equivalently, of codimension 1 in *V*.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] If *V* is a vector space, one distinguishes "vector hyperplanes" (which are linear subspaces, and therefore must pass through the origin) and "affine hyperplanes" (which need not pass through the origin; they can be obtained by translation of a vector hyperplane).
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] A hyperplane in a Euclidean space separates that space into two half spaces, and defines a reflection that fixes the hyperplane and interchanges those two half spaces.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] Several specific types of hyperplanes are defined with properties that are well suited for particular purposes.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] Some of these specializations are described here.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] An **affine hyperplane** is an affine subspace of codimension 1 in an affine space.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] As an example, a point is a hyperplane in 1-dimensional space, a line is a hyperplane in 2-dimensional space, and a plane is a hyperplane in 3-dimensional space.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] A line in 3-dimensional space is not a hyperplane, and does not separate the space into two parts (the complement of such a line is connected).
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] Any hyperplane of a Euclidean space has exactly two unit normal vectors: $\pm {\hat {n}}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] Affine hyperplanes are used to define decision boundaries in many machine learning algorithms such as linear-combination (oblique) decision trees, and perceptrons.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] In a vector space, a vector hyperplane is a subspace of codimension 1, only possibly shifted from the origin by a vector, in which case it is referred to as a flat.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] Such a hyperplane is the solution of a single linear equation.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] In projective space, a hyperplane does not divide the space into two parts; rather, it takes two hyperplanes to separate points and divide up the space.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] The reason for this is that the space essentially "wraps around" so that both sides of a lone hyperplane are connected to each other.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] In convex geometry, two disjoint convex sets in n-dimensional Euclidean space are separated by a hyperplane, a result called the hyperplane separation theorem.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] In machine learning, hyperplanes are a key tool to create support vector machines for such tasks as computer vision and natural language processing.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] In multiple linear regression with more than two regressors, the datapoint and its predicted value via a linear model is a hyperplane.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] In astronomy, hyperplanes can be used to calculate shortest distance between star systems, galaxies and celestial bodies with regard of general relativity and curvature of space-time as optimized geodesic or paths influenced by gravitational fields.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] The dihedral angle between two non-parallel hyperplanes of a Euclidean space is the angle between the corresponding normal vectors.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] The product of the transformations in the two hyperplanes is a rotation whose axis is the subspace of codimension 2 obtained by intersecting the hyperplanes, and whose angle is twice the angle between the hyperplanes.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] A hyperplane H is called a "support" hyperplane of the polyhedron P if P is contained in one of the two closed half-spaces bounded by H and $H\cap P\neq \varnothing$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] The intersection of P and H is defined to be a "face" of the polyhedron.
[src:support-vector-machine/hyperplane] The theory of polyhedra and the dimension of the faces are analyzed by looking at these intersections involving hyperplanes.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] In machine learning, **kernel machines** are a class of algorithms for pattern analysis, whose best known member is the support-vector machine (SVM).
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] These methods involve using linear classifiers to solve nonlinear problems.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] The general task of pattern analysis is to find and study general types of relations (for example clusters, rankings, principal components, correlations, classifications) in datasets.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] The feature map in kernel machines is infinite dimensional but only requires a finite dimensional matrix from user-input according to the representer theorem.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Kernel machines are slow to compute for datasets larger than a couple of thousand examples without parallel processing.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] This operation is often computationally cheaper than the explicit computation of the coordinates.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] This approach is called the "**kernel trick**".
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Kernel functions have been introduced for sequence data, graphs, text, images, as well as vectors.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Algorithms capable of operating with kernels include the kernel perceptron, support-vector machines (SVM), Gaussian processes, principal components analysis (PCA), canonical correlation analysis, ridge regression, spectral clustering, linear adaptive filters and many others.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Most kernel algorithms are based on convex optimization or eigenproblems and are statistically well-founded.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Typically, their statistical properties are analyzed using statistical learning theory (for example, using Rademacher complexity).
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Kernel methods can be thought of as instance-based learners: rather than learning some fixed set of parameters corresponding to the features of their inputs, they instead "remember" the i -th training example $(\mathbf {x} _{i},y_{i})$ and learn for it a corresponding weight $w_{i}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Prediction for unlabeled inputs, i.e., those not in the training set, are treated by the application of a similarity function k , called a **kernel**, between the unlabeled input $\mathbf {x'}$ and each of the training inputs $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Kernel classifiers were described as early as the 1960s, with the invention of the kernel perceptron.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] They rose to great prominence with the popularity of the support-vector machine (SVM) in the 1990s, when the SVM was found to be competitive with neural networks on tasks such as handwriting recognition.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] The kernel trick avoids the explicit mapping that is needed to get linear learning algorithms to learn a nonlinear function or decision boundary.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] For all $\mathbf {x}$ and $\mathbf {x'}$ in the input space ${\mathcal {X}}$ , certain functions $k(\mathbf {x} ,\mathbf {x'} )$ can be expressed as an inner product in another space ${\mathcal {V}}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] The function $k\colon {\mathcal {X}}\times {\mathcal {X}}\to \mathbb {R}$ is often referred to as a *kernel* or a *kernel function*.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] The word "kernel" is used in mathematics to denote a weighting function for a weighted sum or integral.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Certain problems in machine learning have more structure than an arbitrary weighting function k .
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] On the other hand, an explicit representation for $\varphi$ is not necessary, as long as ${\mathcal {V}}$ is an inner product space.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] The alternative follows from Mercer's theorem: an implicitly defined function $\varphi$ exists whenever the space ${\mathcal {X}}$ can be equipped with a suitable measure ensuring the function k satisfies Mercer's condition.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Mercer's theorem is similar to a generalization of the result from linear algebra that associates an inner product to any positive-definite matrix.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] In fact, Mercer's condition can be reduced to this simpler case.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Some algorithms that depend on arbitrary relationships in the native space ${\mathcal {X}}$ would, in fact, have a linear interpretation in a different setting: the range space of $\varphi$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] The linear interpretation gives us insight about the algorithm.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Furthermore, there is often no need to compute $\varphi$ directly during computation, as is the case with support-vector machines.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Some cite this running time shortcut as the primary benefit.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Researchers also use it to justify the meanings and properties of existing algorithms.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Theoretically, a Gram matrix $\mathbf {K} \in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ with respect to $\{\mathbf {x} _{1},\dotsc ,\mathbf {x} _{n}\}$ (sometimes also called a "kernel matrix"), where $K_{ij}=k(\mathbf {x} _{i},\mathbf {x} _{j})$ , must be positive semi-definite (PSD).
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Empirically, for machine learning heuristics, choices of a function k that do not satisfy Mercer's condition may still perform reasonably if k at least approximates the intuitive idea of similarity.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Regardless of whether k is a Mercer kernel, k may still be referred to as a "kernel".
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] If the kernel function k is also a covariance function as used in Gaussian processes, then the Gram matrix $\mathbf {K}$ can also be called a covariance matrix.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-method] Application areas of kernel methods are diverse and include geostatistics, kriging, inverse distance weighting, 3D reconstruction, bioinformatics, cheminformatics, information extraction and handwriting recognition.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] The term **kernel** is used in statistical analysis to refer to a window function.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] The term "kernel" has several distinct meanings in different branches of statistics.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] In statistics, especially in Bayesian statistics, the kernel of a probability density function (pdf) or probability mass function (pmf) is the form of the pdf or pmf in which any factors that are not functions of any of the variables in the domain are omitted.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] Note that such factors may well be functions of the parameters of the pdf or pmf.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] These factors form part of the normalization factor of the probability distribution, and are unnecessary in many situations.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] For example, in pseudo-random number sampling, most sampling algorithms ignore the normalization factor.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] In addition, in Bayesian analysis of conjugate prior distributions, the normalization factors are generally ignored during the calculations, and only the kernel considered.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] At the end, the form of the kernel is examined, and if it matches a known distribution, the normalization factor can be reinstated.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] Otherwise, it may be unnecessary (for example, if the distribution only needs to be sampled from).
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] For many distributions, the kernel can be written in closed form, but not the normalization constant.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] Note that the factor in front of the exponential has been omitted, even though it contains the parameter $\sigma ^{2}$ , because it is not a function of the domain variable x .
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] The kernel of a reproducing kernel Hilbert space is used in the suite of techniques known as kernel methods to perform tasks such as statistical classification, regression analysis, and cluster analysis on data in an implicit space.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] This usage is particularly common in machine learning.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] In nonparametric statistics, a kernel is a weighting function used in non-parametric estimation techniques.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] Kernels are used in kernel density estimation to estimate random variables' density functions, or in kernel regression to estimate the conditional expectation of a random variable.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] Kernels are also used in time series, in the use of the periodogram to estimate the spectral density where they are known as window functions.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] An additional use is in the estimation of a time-varying intensity for a point process where window functions (kernels) are convolved with time-series data.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] Commonly, kernel widths must also be specified when running a non-parametric estimation.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] The first requirement ensures that the method of kernel density estimation results in a probability density function.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] The second requirement ensures that the average of the corresponding distribution is equal to that of the sample used.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] If *K* is a kernel, then so is the function *K** defined by *K**(*u*) = λ*K*(λ*u*), where λ > 0.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] This can be used to select a scale that is appropriate for the data.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] Several types of kernel functions are commonly used: uniform, triangle, Epanechnikov, quartic (biweight), tricube, triweight, Gaussian, quadratic and cosine.
[src:support-vector-machine/kernel-statistics] In the table below, if K is given with a bounded support, then $K(u)=0$ for values of *u* lying outside the support.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The most common form of regression analysis is linear regression, in which one finds the line (or a more complex linear combination) that most closely fits the data according to a specific mathematical criterion.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For example, the method of ordinary least squares computes the unique line (or hyperplane) that minimizes the sum of squared differences between the true data and that line (or hyperplane).
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For specific mathematical reasons (see linear regression), this allows the researcher to estimate the conditional expectation (or population average value) of the dependent variable when the independent variables take on a given set of values.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Less common forms of regression use slightly different procedures to estimate alternative location parameters (e.g., quantile regression or Necessary Condition Analysis) or estimate the conditional expectation across a broader collection of non-linear models (e.g., nonparametric regression).
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Regression analysis is primarily used for two conceptually distinct purposes.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] First, regression analysis is widely used for prediction and forecasting, where its use has substantial overlap with the field of machine learning.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Second, in some situations regression analysis can be used to infer causal relationships between the independent and dependent variables.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Importantly, regressions by themselves only reveal relationships between a dependent variable and a collection of independent variables in a fixed dataset.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] To use regressions for prediction or to infer causal relationships, respectively, a researcher must carefully justify why existing relationships have predictive power for a new context or why a relationship between two variables has a causal interpretation.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The latter is especially important when researchers hope to estimate causal relationships using observational data.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] He also distinguished between two inhomogeneous sets of data and might have thought of an *optimal* solution in terms of bias, though not in terms of effectiveness." He previously used an averaging method in his 1671 work on Newton's rings, which was unprecedented at the time.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The method of least squares was published by Legendre in 1805, and by Gauss in 1809.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Legendre and Gauss both applied the method to the problem of determining, from astronomical observations, the orbits of bodies about the Sun (mostly comets, but also later the then newly discovered minor planets).
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Gauss published a further development of the theory of least squares in 1821, including a version of the Gauss–Markov theorem.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The term "regression" was coined by Francis Galton in the 19th century to describe a biological phenomenon.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The phenomenon was that the heights of descendants of tall ancestors tend to regress down towards a normal average (a phenomenon also known as regression toward the mean).
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For Galton, regression had only this biological meaning, but his work was later extended by Udny Yule and Karl Pearson to a more general statistical context.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] In the work of Yule and Pearson, the joint distribution of the response and explanatory variables is assumed to be Gaussian.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Fisher assumed that the conditional distribution of the response variable is Gaussian, but the joint distribution need not be.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] In this respect, Fisher's assumption is closer to Gauss's formulation of 1821.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] In the 1950s and 1960s, economists used electromechanical desk calculators to calculate regressions.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Before 1970, it sometimes took up to 24 hours to receive the result from one regression.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Regression methods continue to be an area of active research.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Modern regression analysis is typically done with statistical and spreadsheet software packages on computers as well as on handheld scientific and graphing calculators.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] In practice, researchers first select a model they would like to estimate and then use their chosen method (e.g., ordinary least squares) to estimate the parameters of that model.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] In various fields of application, different terminologies are used in place of dependent and independent variables.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] In the standard regression model, the independent variables $X_{i}$ are assumed to be free of error.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The errors-in-variables model can be used if the independent variables are assumed to contain errors.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Other modifications to the standard regression model can be made to account for various scenarios, such as situations involving omitted variables, confounding variables or endogeneity.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The researchers' goal is to estimate the function $f(X_{i},\beta )$ that most closely fits the data.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] To carry out regression analysis, the form of the function f must be specified.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Sometimes the form of this function is based on knowledge about the relationship between $Y_{i}$ and $X_{i}$ that does not rely on the data.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] If no such knowledge is available, a flexible or convenient form for f is chosen.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For example, a simple univariate regression may propose $f(X_{i},\beta )=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{i}$ , suggesting that the researcher believes $Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{i}+e_{i}$ to be a reasonable approximation for the statistical process generating the data.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Once researchers determine their preferred statistical model, different forms of regression analysis provide tools to estimate the parameters $\beta$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For example, least squares (including its most common variant, ordinary least squares) finds the value of $\beta$ that minimizes the sum of squared errors $\sum _{i}(Y_{i}-f(X_{i},\beta ))^{2}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] A given regression method will ultimately provide an estimate of $\beta$ , usually denoted ${\hat {\beta }}$ to distinguish the estimate from the true (unknown) parameter value that generated the data.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Using this estimate, the researcher can then use the *fitted value* ${\hat {Y_{i}}}=f(X_{i},{\hat {\beta }})$ for prediction or to assess the accuracy of the model in explaining the data.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Whether the researcher is intrinsically interested in the estimate ${\hat {\beta }}$ or the predicted value ${\hat {Y_{i}}}$ will depend on context and their goals.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] As described in ordinary least squares, least squares is widely used because the estimated function $f(X_{i},{\hat {\beta }})$ approximates the conditional expectation $E(Y_{i}|X_{i})$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] However, alternative variants (e.g., least absolute deviations or quantile regression) are useful when researchers want to model other functions $f(X_{i},\beta )$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] There must be sufficient data to estimate a regression model.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For example, suppose that a researcher has access to N rows of data with one dependent and two independent variables: $(Y_{i},X_{1i},X_{2i})$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Suppose further that the researcher wants to estimate a bivariate linear model via least squares: $Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{1i}+\beta _{2}X_{2i}+e_{i}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] To understand why there are infinitely many options, note that the system of $N=2$ equations is to be solved for 3 unknowns, which makes the system underdetermined.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Alternatively, one can visualize infinitely many 3-dimensional planes that go through $N=2$ fixed points.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] More generally, to estimate a least squares model with k distinct parameters, one must have $N\geq k$ distinct data points.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] If $N>k$ , then there does not generally exist a set of parameters that will perfectly fit the data.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The quantity $N-k$ appears often in regression analysis, and is referred to as the degrees of freedom in the model.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Moreover, to estimate a least squares model, the independent variables $(X_{1i},X_{2i},...,X_{ki})$ must be linearly independent: one must *not* be able to reconstruct any of the independent variables by adding and multiplying the remaining independent variables.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] As discussed in ordinary least squares, this condition ensures that $X^{T}X$ is an invertible matrix and therefore that a unique solution ${\hat {\beta }}$ exists.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] By itself, a regression is just a computation performed on a set of data.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] In order to interpret the resultant regression as a meaningful statistical model that quantifies real-world relationships, researchers often rely on a number of classical assumptions.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] A handful of conditions are sufficient for the least-squares estimator to possess desirable properties: in particular, the Gauss–Markov assumptions imply that the parameter estimates will be unbiased, consistent, and efficient in the class of linear unbiased estimators.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Practitioners have developed a variety of methods to maintain some or all of these desirable properties in real-world settings, because these classical assumptions are unlikely to hold exactly.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For example, modeling errors-in-variables can lead to reasonable estimates independent variables are measured with errors.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Heteroscedasticity-consistent standard errors allow the variance of $e_{i}$ to change across values of $X_{i}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Correlated errors that exist within subsets of the data or follow specific patterns can be handled using *clustered standard errors, geographic weighted regression*, or Newey–West standard errors, among other techniques.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] When rows of data correspond to locations in space, the choice of how to model $e_{i}$ within geographic units can have important consequences.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The subfield of econometrics is largely focused on developing techniques that allow researchers to make reasonable real-world conclusions in real-world settings, where classical assumptions do not hold exactly.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] In linear regression, the model specification is that the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ is a linear combination of the *parameters* (but need not be linear in the *independent variables*).
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] In multiple linear regression, there are several independent variables or functions of independent variables.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] In both cases, $\varepsilon _{i}$ is an error term and the subscript i indexes a particular observation.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The residual, $e_{i}=y_{i}-{\widehat {y}}_{i}$ , is the difference between the value of the dependent variable predicted by the model, ${\widehat {y}}_{i}$ , and the true value of the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] One method of estimation is ordinary least squares.
