[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Once a regression model has been constructed, it may be important to confirm the goodness of fit of the model and the statistical significance of the estimated parameters.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Commonly used checks of goodness of fit include the R-squared, analyses of the pattern of residuals and hypothesis testing.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Statistical significance can be checked by an F-test of the overall fit, followed by t-tests of individual parameters.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Interpretations of these diagnostic tests rest heavily on the model's assumptions.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Although examination of the residuals can be used to invalidate a model, the results of a t-test or F-test are sometimes more difficult to interpret if the model's assumptions are violated.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For example, if the error term does not have a normal distribution, in small samples the estimated parameters will not follow normal distributions and complicate inference.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] With relatively large samples, however, a central limit theorem can be invoked such that hypothesis testing may proceed using asymptotic approximations.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Limited dependent variables, which are response variables that are categorical or constrained to fall only in a certain range, often arise in econometrics.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The response variable may be non-continuous ("limited" to lie on some subset of the real line).
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For binary (zero or one) variables, if analysis proceeds with least-squares linear regression, the model is called the linear probability model.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Nonlinear models for binary dependent variables include the probit and logit model.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The multivariate probit model is a standard method of estimating a joint relationship between several binary dependent variables and some independent variables.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For categorical variables with more than two values there is the multinomial logit.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For ordinal variables with more than two values, there are the ordered logit and ordered probit models.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Censored regression models may be used when the dependent variable is only sometimes observed, and Heckman correction type models may be used when the sample is not randomly selected from the population of interest.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] An alternative to such procedures is linear regression based on polychoric correlation (or polyserial correlations) between the categorical variables.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Such procedures differ in the assumptions made about the distribution of the variables in the population.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] If the variable is positive with low values and represents the repetition of the occurrence of an event, then count models like the Poisson regression or the negative binomial model may be used.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] When the model function is not linear in the parameters, the sum of squares must be minimized by an iterative procedure.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] This introduces many complications which are summarized in Differences between linear and non-linear least squares.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Regression models ***predict*** a value of the *Y* variable given known values of the *X* variables.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Prediction *within* the range of values in the dataset used for model-fitting is known informally as *interpolation*.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Prediction *outside* this range of the data is known as *extrapolation*.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Performing extrapolation relies strongly on the regression assumptions.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The further the extrapolation goes outside the data, the more room there is for the model to fail due to differences between the assumptions and the sample data or the true values.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] A *prediction interval* that represents the uncertainty may accompany the point prediction.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Such intervals tend to expand rapidly as the values of the independent variable(s) moved outside the range covered by the observed data.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For such reasons and others, some tend to say that it might be unwise to undertake extrapolation.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The assumption of a particular form for the relation between *Y* and *X* is another source of uncertainty.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] A properly conducted regression analysis will include an assessment of how well the assumed form is matched by the observed data, but it can only do so within the range of values of the independent variables actually available.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] This means that any extrapolation is particularly reliant on the assumptions being made about the structural form of the regression relationship.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] If this knowledge includes the fact that the dependent variable cannot go outside a certain range of values, this can be made use of in selecting the model – even if the observed dataset has no values particularly near such bounds.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] The implications of this step of choosing an appropriate functional form for the regression can be great when extrapolation is considered.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] At a minimum, it can ensure that any extrapolation arising from a fitted model is "realistic" (or in accord with what is known).
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] There are no generally agreed methods for relating the number of observations versus the number of independent variables in the model.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] One method conjectured by Good and Hardin is $N=m^{n}$ , where N is the sample size, n is the number of independent variables and m is the number of observations needed to reach the desired precision if the model had only one independent variable.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] For example, a researcher is building a linear regression model using a dataset that contains 1000 patients ( N ).
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] All major statistical software packages perform least squares regression analysis and inference.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Simple linear regression and multiple regression using least squares can be done in some spreadsheet applications and on some calculators.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] While many statistical software packages can perform various types of nonparametric and robust regression, these methods are less standardized.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Different software packages implement different methods, and a method with a given name may be implemented differently in different packages.
[src:support-vector-machine/regression-analysis] Specialized regression software has been developed for use in fields such as survey analysis and neuroimaging.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] When classification is performed by a computer, statistical methods are normally used to develop the algorithm.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Often, the individual observations are analyzed into a set of quantifiable properties, known variously as explanatory variables or *features*.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] These properties may variously be categorical (e.g.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"), integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email) or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Other classifiers work by comparing observations to previous observations by means of a similarity or distance function.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] An algorithm that implements classification, especially in a concrete implementation, is known as a **classifier**.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] The term "classifier" sometimes also refers to the mathematical function, implemented by a classification algorithm, that maps input data to a category.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Terminology across fields is quite varied.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] In machine learning, the observations are often known as *instances*, the explanatory variables are termed *features* (grouped into a feature vector), and the possible categories to be predicted are *classes*.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Other fields may use different terminology: e.g. in community ecology, the term "classification" normally refers to cluster analysis.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Classification and clustering are examples of the more general problem of pattern recognition, which is the assignment of some sort of output value to a given input value.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] A common subclass of classification is probabilistic classification.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Algorithms of this nature use statistical inference to find the best class for a given instance.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Unlike other algorithms, which simply output a "best" class, probabilistic algorithms output a probability of the instance being a member of each of the possible classes.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] The best class is normally then selected as the one with the highest probability.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Early work on statistical classification was undertaken by Fisher, in the context of two-group problems, leading to Fisher's linear discriminant function as the rule for assigning a group to a new observation.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] This early work assumed that data-values within each of the two groups had a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] The extension of this same context to more than two groups has also been considered with a restriction imposed that the classification rule should be linear.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Unlike frequentist procedures, Bayesian classification procedures provide a natural way of taking into account any available information about the relative sizes of the different groups within the overall population.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Bayesian procedures tend to be computationally expensive and, in the days before Markov chain Monte Carlo computations were developed, approximations for Bayesian clustering rules were devised.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Some Bayesian procedures involve the calculation of group-membership probabilities: these provide a more informative outcome than a simple attribution of a single group-label to each new observation.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Classification can be thought of as two separate problems – binary classification and multiclass classification.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] In binary classification, a better understood task, only two classes are involved, whereas multiclass classification involves assigning an object to one of several classes.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Since many classification methods have been developed specifically for binary classification, multiclass classification often requires the combined use of multiple binary classifiers.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Most algorithms describe an individual instance whose category is to be predicted using a feature vector of individual, measurable properties of the instance.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Each property is termed a feature, also known in statistics as an explanatory variable (or independent variable, although features may or may not be statistically independent).
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"); integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email); or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] If the instance is an image, the feature values might correspond to the pixels of an image; if the instance is a piece of text, the feature values might be occurrence frequencies of different words.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Some algorithms work only in terms of discrete data and require that real-valued or integer-valued data be *discretized* into groups (e.g. less than 5, between 5 and 10, or greater than 10).
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] A large number of algorithms for classification can be phrased in terms of a linear function that assigns a score to each possible category *k* by combining the feature vector of an instance with a vector of weights, using a dot product.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] The predicted category is the one with the highest score.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] In discrete choice theory, where instances represent people and categories represent choices, the score is considered the utility associated with person *i* choosing category *k*.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Algorithms with this basic setup are known as linear classifiers.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] What distinguishes them is the procedure for determining (training) the optimal weights/coefficients and the way that the score is interpreted.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Since no single form of classification is appropriate for all data sets, a large toolkit of classification algorithms has been developed.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] Choices between different possible algorithms are frequently made on the basis of quantitative evaluation of accuracy.
[src:support-vector-machine/statistical-classification] In some of these, it is employed as a data mining procedure, while in others more detailed statistical modeling is undertaken.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] In machine learning, **support vector machines** (**SVMs**, also **support vector networks**) are supervised max-margin models with associated learning algorithms that analyze data for classification and regression analysis.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Developed at AT&T Bell Laboratories, SVMs are one of the most studied models, being based on statistical learning frameworks of VC theory proposed by Vapnik (1982, 1995) and Chervonenkis (1974).
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Thus, SVMs use the kernel trick to implicitly map their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces, where linear classification can be performed.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Being max-margin models, SVMs are resilient to noisy data (e.g., misclassified examples).
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] SVMs can also be used for regression tasks, where the objective becomes $\epsilon$ -sensitive.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The support vector clustering algorithm, created by Hava Siegelmann and Vladimir Vapnik, applies the statistics of support vectors, developed in the support vector machines algorithm, to categorize unlabeled data.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] These data sets require unsupervised learning approaches, which attempt to find natural clustering of the data into groups, and then to map new data according to these clusters.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The popularity of SVMs is likely due to their amenability to theoretical analysis, and their flexibility in being applied to a wide variety of tasks, including structured prediction problems.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] It is not clear that SVMs have better predictive performance than other linear models, such as logistic regression and linear regression.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Classifying data is a common task in machine learning.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Suppose some given data points each belong to one of two classes, and the goal is to decide which class a *new* data point will be in.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] In the case of support vector machines, a data point is viewed as a p -dimensional vector (a list of p numbers), and we want to know whether we can separate such points with a $(p-1)$ -dimensional hyperplane.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] There are many hyperplanes that might classify the data.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] One reasonable choice as the best hyperplane is the one that represents the largest separation, or margin, between the two classes.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] So we choose the hyperplane so that the distance from it to the nearest data point on each side is maximized.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] If such a hyperplane exists, it is known as the *maximum-margin hyperplane* and the linear classifier it defines is known as a *maximum-margin classifier*; or equivalently, the *perceptron of optimal stability*.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] More formally, a support vector machine constructs a hyperplane or set of hyperplanes in a high or infinite-dimensional space, which can be used for classification, regression, or other tasks like outlier detection.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Intuitively, a good separation is achieved by the hyperplane that has the largest distance to the nearest training-data point of any class (so-called functional margin), since in general the larger the margin, the lower the generalization error of the classifier.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] A lower generalization error means that the implementer is less likely to experience overfitting.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Whereas the original problem may be stated in a finite-dimensional space, it often happens that the sets to discriminate are not linearly separable in that space.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] For this reason, it was proposed that the original finite-dimensional space be mapped into a much higher-dimensional space, presumably making the separation easier in that space.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The hyperplanes in the higher-dimensional space are defined as the set of points whose dot product with a vector in that space is constant, where such a set of vectors is an orthogonal (and thus minimal) set of vectors that defines a hyperplane.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The vectors defining the hyperplanes can be chosen to be linear combinations with parameters $\alpha _{i}$ of images of feature vectors $x_{i}$ that occur in the data base.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] In this way, the sum of kernels above can be used to measure the relative nearness of each test point to the data points originating in one or the other of the sets to be discriminated.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Note the fact that the set of points x mapped into any hyperplane can be quite convoluted as a result, allowing much more complex discrimination between sets that are not convex at all in the original space.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The original SVM algorithm was invented by Vladimir N.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] In 1992, Bernhard Boser, Isabelle Guyon and Vladimir Vapnik suggested a way to create nonlinear classifiers by applying the kernel trick to maximum-margin hyperplanes.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The "soft margin" incarnation, as is commonly used in software packages, was proposed by Corinna Cortes and Vapnik in 1993 and published in 1995.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] We are given a training dataset of n points of the form $(\mathbf {x} _{1},y_{1}),\ldots ,(\mathbf {x} _{n},y_{n}),$ where the $y_{i}$ are either 1 or −1, each indicating the class to which the point $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ belongs.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Each $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ is a p -dimensional real vector.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Any hyperplane can be written as the set of points $\mathbf {x}$ satisfying $\mathbf {w} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {x} -b=0,$ where $\mathbf {w}$ is the (not necessarily normalized) normal vector to the hyperplane.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] This is much like Hesse normal form, except that $\mathbf {w}$ is not necessarily a unit vector.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The parameter ${\tfrac {b}{\|\mathbf {w} \|}}$ determines the offset of the hyperplane from the origin along the normal vector $\mathbf {w}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] If the training data is linearly separable, we can select two parallel hyperplanes that separate the two classes of data, so that the distance between them is as large as possible.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The region bounded by these two hyperplanes is called the "margin", and the maximum-margin hyperplane is the hyperplane that lies halfway between them.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] (anything on or below this boundary is of the other class, with label −1).
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Geometrically, the distance between these two hyperplanes is ${\tfrac {2}{\|\mathbf {w} \|}}$ , so to maximize the distance between the planes we want to minimize $\|\mathbf {w} \|$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The distance is computed using the distance from a point to a plane equation.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The $\mathbf {w}$ and b that solve this problem determine the final classifier, $\mathbf {x} \mapsto \operatorname {sgn}(\mathbf {w} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {x} -b)$ , where $\operatorname {sgn}(\cdot )$ is the sign function.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] An important consequence of this geometric description is that the max-margin hyperplane is completely determined by those $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ that lie nearest to it (explained below).
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] These $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ are called *support vectors*.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] This function is zero if the constraint in **(1)** is satisfied, in other words, if $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ lies on the correct side of the margin.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] For data on the wrong side of the margin, the function's value is proportional to the distance from the margin.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] where the parameter $C>0$ determines the trade-off between increasing the margin size and ensuring that the $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ lie on the correct side of the margin (Note we can add a weight to either term in the equation above).
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Thus, for large values of C , it will behave similar to the hard-margin SVM, if the input data are linearly classifiable, but will still learn if a classification rule is viable or not.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The original maximum-margin hyperplane algorithm proposed by Vapnik in 1963 constructed a linear classifier.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] However, in 1992, Bernhard Boser, Isabelle Guyon and Vladimir Vapnik suggested a way to create nonlinear classifiers by applying the kernel trick (originally proposed by Aizerman et al.) to maximum-margin hyperplanes.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The kernel trick, where dot products are replaced by kernels, is easily derived in the dual representation of the SVM problem.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] This allows the algorithm to fit the maximum-margin hyperplane in a transformed feature space.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The transformation may be nonlinear and the transformed space high-dimensional; although the classifier is a hyperplane in the transformed feature space, it may be nonlinear in the original input space.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] It is noteworthy that working in a higher-dimensional feature space increases the generalization error of support vector machines, although given enough samples the algorithm still performs well.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The kernel is related to the transform $\varphi (\mathbf {x} _{i})$ by the equation $k(\mathbf {x} _{i},\mathbf {x} _{j})=\varphi (\mathbf {x} _{i})\cdot \varphi (\mathbf {x} _{j})$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The value **w** is also in the transformed space, with ${\textstyle \mathbf {w} =\sum _{i}\alpha _{i}y_{i}\varphi (\mathbf {x} _{i})}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Dot products with **w** for classification can again be computed by the kernel trick, i.e. ${\textstyle \mathbf {w} \cdot \varphi (\mathbf {x} )=\sum _{i}\alpha _{i}y_{i}k(\mathbf {x} _{i},\mathbf {x} )}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] We focus on the soft-margin classifier since, as noted above, choosing a sufficiently small value for $\lambda$ yields the hard-margin classifier for linearly classifiable input data.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The classical approach, which involves reducing **(2)** to a quadratic programming problem, is detailed below.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Then, more recent approaches such as sub-gradient descent and coordinate descent will be discussed.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Minimizing **(2)** can be rewritten as a constrained optimization problem with a differentiable objective function in the following way.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Since the dual maximization problem is a quadratic function of the $c_{i}$ subject to linear constraints, it is efficiently solvable by quadratic programming algorithms.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Moreover, $c_{i}=0$ exactly when $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ lies on the correct side of the margin, and $0<c_{i}<(2n\lambda )^{-1}$ when $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ lies on the margin's boundary.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] It follows that $\mathbf {w}$ can be written as a linear combination of the support vectors.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The coefficients $c_{i}$ can be solved for using quadratic programming, as before.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Recent algorithms for finding the SVM classifier include sub-gradient descent and coordinate descent.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Both techniques have proven to offer significant advantages over the traditional approach when dealing with large, sparse datasets—sub-gradient methods are especially efficient when there are many training examples, and coordinate descent when the dimension of the feature space is high.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Note that f is a convex function of $\mathbf {w}$ and b .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] As such, traditional gradient descent (or SGD) methods can be adapted, where instead of taking a step in the direction of the function's gradient, a step is taken in the direction of a vector selected from the function's sub-gradient.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] This approach has the advantage that, for certain implementations, the number of iterations does not scale with n , the number of data points.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] For each $i\in \{1,\,\ldots ,\,n\}$ , iteratively, the coefficient $c_{i}$ is adjusted in the direction of $\partial f/\partial c_{i}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Then, the resulting vector of coefficients $(c_{1}',\,\ldots ,\,c_{n}')$ is projected onto the nearest vector of coefficients that satisfies the given constraints.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] (Typically Euclidean distances are used.) The process is then repeated until a near-optimal vector of coefficients is obtained.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The resulting algorithm is extremely fast in practice, although few performance guarantees have been proven.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The soft-margin support vector machine described above is an example of an empirical risk minimization (ERM) algorithm for the *hinge loss*.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Seen this way, support vector machines belong to a natural class of algorithms for statistical inference, and many of its unique features are due to the behavior of the hinge loss.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] This perspective can provide further insight into how and why SVMs work, and allow us to better analyze their statistical properties.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] In supervised learning, one is given a set of training examples $X_{1}\ldots X_{n}$ with labels $y_{1}\ldots y_{n}$ , and wishes to predict $y_{n+1}$ given $X_{n+1}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] To do so one forms a hypothesis, f , such that $f(X_{n+1})$ is a "good" approximation of $y_{n+1}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] A "good" approximation is usually defined with the help of a *loss function,* $\ell (y,z)$ , which characterizes how bad z is as a prediction of y .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] In most cases, we don't know the joint distribution of $X_{n+1},\,y_{n+1}$ outright.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] This approach is called *empirical risk minimization,* or ERM.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] In order for the minimization problem to have a well-defined solution, we have to place constraints on the set ${\mathcal {H}}$ of hypotheses being considered.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] If ${\mathcal {H}}$ is a normed space (as is the case for SVM), a particularly effective technique is to consider only those hypotheses f for which $\lVert f\rVert _{\mathcal {H}}<k$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] More generally, ${\mathcal {R}}(f)$ can be some measure of the complexity of the hypothesis f , so that simpler hypotheses are preferred.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] From this perspective, SVM is closely related to other fundamental classification algorithms such as regularized least-squares and logistic regression.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The difference between the hinge loss and these other loss functions is best stated in terms of *target functions -* the function that minimizes expected risk for a given pair of random variables $X,\,y$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] In particular, let $y_{x}$ denote y conditional on the event that $X=x$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] For the square-loss, the target function is the conditional expectation function, $f_{sq}(x)=\mathbb {E} \left[y_{x}\right]$ ; For the logistic loss, it's the logit function, $f_{\log }(x)=\ln \left(p_{x}/({1-p_{x}})\right)$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] While both of these target functions yield the correct classifier, as $\operatorname {sgn}(f_{sq})=\operatorname {sgn}(f_{\log })=f^{*}$ , they give us more information than we need.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] In fact, they give us enough information to completely describe the distribution of $y_{x}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] On the other hand, one can check that the target function for the hinge loss is *exactly* $f^{*}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Thus, in a sufficiently rich hypothesis space—or equivalently, for an appropriately chosen kernel—the SVM classifier will converge to the simplest function (in terms of ${\mathcal {R}}$ ) that correctly classifies the data.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] This extends the geometric interpretation of SVM—for linear classification, the empirical risk is minimized by any function whose margins lie between the support vectors, and the simplest of these is the max-margin classifier.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] SVMs belong to a family of generalized linear classifiers and can be interpreted as an extension of the perceptron.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] They can also be considered a special case of Tikhonov regularization.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] A special property is that they simultaneously minimize the empirical *classification error* and maximize the *geometric margin*; hence they are also known as **maximum margin classifiers**.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] A comparison of the SVM to other classifiers has been made by Meyer, Leisch and Hornik.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The effectiveness of SVM depends on the selection of kernel, the kernel's parameters, and soft margin parameter $\lambda$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] A common choice is a Gaussian kernel, which has a single parameter *$\gamma$*.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Typically, each combination of parameter choices is checked using cross validation, and the parameters with best cross-validation accuracy are picked.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Alternatively, recent work in Bayesian optimization can be used to select $\lambda$ and *$\gamma$* , often requiring the evaluation of far fewer parameter combinations than grid search.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The final model, which is used for testing and for classifying new data, is then trained on the whole training set using the selected parameters.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Multiclass SVM aims to assign labels to instances by using support vector machines, where the labels are drawn from a finite set of several elements.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The dominant approach for doing so is to reduce the single multiclass problem into multiple binary classification problems.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Crammer and Singer proposed a multiclass SVM method which casts the multiclass classification problem into a single optimization problem, rather than decomposing it into multiple binary classification problems.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] See also Lee, Lin and Wahba and Van den Burg and Groenen.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Transductive support vector machines extend SVMs in that they could also treat partially labeled data in semi-supervised learning by following the principles of transduction.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Transductive support vector machines were introduced by Vladimir N.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Structured support-vector machine is an extension of the traditional SVM model.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] While the SVM model is primarily designed for binary classification, multiclass classification, and regression tasks, structured SVM broadens its application to handle general structured output labels, for example parse trees, classification with taxonomies, sequence alignment and many more.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] A version of SVM for regression was proposed in 1996 by Vladimir N.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] This method is called support vector regression (SVR).
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The model produced by support vector classification (as described above) depends only on a subset of the training data, because the cost function for building the model does not care about training points that lie beyond the margin.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Analogously, the model produced by SVR depends only on a subset of the training data, because the cost function for building the model ignores any training data close to the model prediction.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Another SVM version known as least-squares support vector machine (LS-SVM) has been proposed by Suykens and Vandewalle.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] where $x_{i}$ is a training sample with target value $y_{i}$ .
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The inner product plus intercept $\langle w,x_{i}\rangle +b$ is the prediction for that sample, and $\varepsilon$ is a free parameter that serves as a threshold: all predictions have to be within an $\varepsilon$ range of the true predictions.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Slack variables are usually added into the above to allow for errors and to allow approximation in the case the above problem is infeasible.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] In 2011 it was shown by Polson and Scott that the SVM admits a Bayesian interpretation through the technique of data augmentation.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] In this approach the SVM is viewed as a graphical model (where the parameters are connected via probability distributions).
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] This extended view allows the application of Bayesian techniques to SVMs, such as flexible feature modeling, automatic hyperparameter tuning, and predictive uncertainty quantification.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] In 2017, a scalable version of the Bayesian SVM was developed by Florian Wenzel, enabling the application of Bayesian SVMs to big data.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Florian Wenzel developed two different versions, a variational inference (VI) scheme for the Bayesian kernel support vector machine (SVM) and a stochastic version (SVI) for the linear Bayesian SVM.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The parameters of the maximum-margin hyperplane are derived by solving the optimization.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] There exist several specialized algorithms for quickly solving the quadratic programming (QP) problem that arises from SVMs, mostly relying on heuristics for breaking the problem down into smaller, more manageable chunks.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Another approach is to use an interior-point method that uses Newton-like iterations to find a solution of the Karush–Kuhn–Tucker conditions of the primal and dual problems.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Instead of solving a sequence of broken-down problems, this approach directly solves the problem altogether.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] To avoid solving a linear system involving the large kernel matrix, a low-rank approximation to the matrix is often used in the kernel trick.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Another common method is Platt's sequential minimal optimization (SMO) algorithm, which breaks the problem down into 2-dimensional sub-problems that are solved analytically, eliminating the need for a numerical optimization algorithm and matrix storage.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] This algorithm is conceptually simple, easy to implement, generally faster, and has better scaling properties for difficult SVM problems.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The special case of linear support vector machines can be solved more efficiently by the same kind of algorithms used to optimize its close cousin, logistic regression; this class of algorithms includes sub-gradient descent (e.g., PEGASOS) and coordinate descent (e.g., LIBLINEAR).
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] LIBLINEAR has some attractive training-time properties.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Each convergence iteration takes time linear in the time taken to read the train data, and the iterations also have a Q-linear convergence property, making the algorithm extremely fast.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] The general kernel SVMs can also be solved more efficiently using sub-gradient descent (e.g.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] P-packSVM), especially when parallelization is allowed.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Kernel SVMs are available in many machine-learning toolkits, including LIBSVM, MATLAB, SAS, SVMlight, kernlab, scikit-learn, Shogun, Weka, Shark, JKernelMachines, OpenCV and others.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Preprocessing of data (standardization) is highly recommended to enhance accuracy of classification.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] There are a few methods of standardization, such as min-max, normalization by decimal scaling, Z-score.
[src:support-vector-machine/support-vector-machine] Subtraction of mean and division by variance of each feature is usually used for SVM.
